      <hedline>
        <hl1>Concerned Conservatives</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Stewardship Project Pres Mark Van Putten letter, prompted by March 10 article on evangelicals combatting global warming, says conversatives are beginning to take lead on environmental issues because they are opposing federal subsidies of environmentally damaging programs</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Conservatives are beginning to lead on environmental issues for reasons beyond stewardship of God's creation and on issues in addition to global warming (''Evangelical Leaders Swing Influence Behind Effort to Combat Global Warming,'' news article, March 10).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Conservatives are beginning to lead on environmental issues for reasons beyond stewardship of God's creation and on issues in addition to global warming (''Evangelical Leaders Swing Influence Behind Effort to Combat Global Warming,'' news article, March 10).</p>
        <p>Increasingly, fiscal conservatives are opposing wasteful federal subsidies of programs that also damage the environment. Free-market entrepreneurs are innovating market-based, cost-effective solutions to environmental problems.</p>
        <p>Thoughtful pro-life conservatives embrace a comprehensive culture of life throughout all of human lives and including non-human life. And social conservatives are coming to understand that common caring for the local environment helps build stronger human communities.</p>
        <p>Conservatives of all types are not only recognizing environmental problems, but are also beginning to take leadership roles in crafting creative new ways to solve them.</p>
        <p>Mark Van Putten  President, Stewardship Project  Reston, Va., March 10, 2005</p>
      </block>
